Sorry if anyone else is bored by this but I find the topic fascinating.

Anyway.

I read your post and realized that it's *social* object permanence the Vargr lack. The Vargr are genetically uplifted pack hunters, hardwired for in-group morality AND an in-group that doesn't exceed their Dunbar's Number, which is rather smaller than the typical human's.

Which is why the idea of swearing fealty to a distant government and a leader they can't see and talk to every day, is incomprehensible to them. They're not unaware that there is a universe outside the pack--but if they don't know them personally, if they don't see and work side by side with them, those other people don't matter, even if they're other Vargr.

This is one reason why so many other cultures' first contacts with the Vargr was when a band of Vargr pirates or bandits descended on their planet, raised the black flag, and began slitting throats. They're predators. It suits their instincts and feels RIGHT to them, the way more peaceful interactions don't.

This has led to a couple of entire Vargr ethnic groups and multiple Vargr-settled worlds getting the thermonuclear Exterminatus laid on their asses by other local polities that were capable of organizing in groups larger than a few hundred and who got sick and tired of visiting colony worlds only to find scorched earth and the gnawed bones of children. At least one time it was done by a human government that had the covert support of numerous Vargr warlords, because the offending group's excessive enthusiasm for mayhem had made it much harder for them to sell their services as mercenaries to non-Vargr governments. The surviving groups are less bloodthirsty. Think of it as evolution in action.

It is an amusing irony--the kind one finds in real-world history, when one looks for them--that the Vargr, who became known to their neighbors by behaving like storybook monsters, are much more afraid of humanity than the reverse.
